result.execSummary:
The defendant Rayshawn Anthony Higgins was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Rayshawn Anthony Higgins in court with attorney Gabriela A Leija.  Defendant Rayshawn Anthony Higgins in custody.  Elizabeth Longo appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.
AS TO COUNTS 1 and 2:    Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.

Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties. 
AS TO COUNTS 1 and 2:  Defendant ordered to serve 90 days in the House of Correction, concurrent to each other.
Defendant to pay all costs, fees and surcharges, to be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds and any remaining balance due by end of extended supervision of 12CF5576.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.
Appeal rights given.
